examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 24 kg/m\u00b2. The ultrasound reveals a single viable fetus with normal anatomy. The placenta is posterior and located 1.5 cm from the internal cervical os.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Placenta previa","Placental abruption","Normal placental position","Low-lying placenta","Vasa previa"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s ultrasound shows a placenta that is 1.5 cm from the internal cervical os at the time of her morphology scan. This finding represents a \u003Cstrong\u003Elow-lying placenta\u003C/strong\u003E, which is defined as a placenta that lies within 2 cm of the internal cervical os but does not cover it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacenta previa\u003C/strong\u003E is specifically diagnosed when the placenta overlies the internal cervical os. This is not the case here as there is a 1.5 cm distance between the placenta and the os.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasa previa\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare condition where fetal blood vessels run through the membranes over the internal cervical os, unprotected by placental tissue or umbilical cord. There is no mention of this finding on ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal placental position\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if the placenta was more than 2 cm from the internal cervical os.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacental abruption\u003C/strong\u003E refers to premature separation of the placenta from the uterine wall, which would present with bleeding and pain, not as an incidental finding on routine ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of a low-lying placenta at morphology scan includes arranging follow-up ultrasound at 32 weeks gestation, as approximately 90% of cases will resolve by then due to differential growth of the lower uterine segment. The patient should be advised to present immediately if any vaginal bleeding occurs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Placental position within 2cm of the internal cervical os at morphology scan (18-22 weeks) requires follow-up ultrasound at 32 weeks.","Low-lying placenta at morphology scan often resolves by third trimester due to differential growth of the lower uterine segment.","Placenta previa is only diagnosed when the placenta overlies the internal cervical os."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RCOG). Placenta praevia and placenta accreta: diagnosis and management: Green-top guideline no. 27a [Internet]. London: RCOG; 2018 [cited 2024 Jun 23]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/placenta-praevia-and-placenta-accreta-diagnosis-and-management-green-top-guideline-no-27a/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53575"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16981"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53575"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T10:11:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T10:13:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9671"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68118"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emo